  "contrast_notes": [
    "primary violet.600 (#6d28d9) on white is ~6.6:1, passing SC 1.4.3 for text and SC 1.4.11 for the control; the brighter violet.500 (#7c3aed, ~5.1:1) is acceptable for large text but reserved mainly for fills and gradients",
    "warning amber.600 (#d97706) uses dark (ink.900) foreground rather than white, since white on amber fails contrast; never place white text on amber/yellow fills",
    "Gradient buttons must guarantee the label meets 4.5:1 against the darkest point of the gradient, not just the lightest",
    "In dark theme, primary is lightened to violet.300/#a78bfa with dark foreground because violet.600 lacks contrast on dark surfaces",
    "fg.muted ink.600 (#4b5563) on white is ~7.5:1; do not drop secondary text below ink.500 (#6b7280, ~4.8:1)"
  ],
  "colour_vision_notes": [
    "Despite the vibrant palette, status meaning is always reinforced with icon and text, never colour alone (SC 1.4.1)",
    "The chart palette leads violet-sky-emerald-amber so the first four series stay separable under deuteranopia and protanopia; rose and emerald are kept non-adjacent to avoid red/green confusion",
    "Saturated rose and emerald can be hard to tell apart for red-green CVD users; rely on order, labels, and direct data labels rather than hue alone in legends"
  ],
  "evidence": [
    "Contrast ratios computed against WCAG 2.2 SC 1.4.3 and 1.4.11",
    "Vibrant violet/indigo SaaS branding mirrors Linear, Stripe, and similar product palettes",
    "Colour-blind-safe ordering follows IBM Carbon and Material data-vis guidance; verify gradients and saturated pairs in a CVD simulator"
  ]
}
